On this Transgender Day of Visibility, we see you and we stand firm knowing your presence makes our community stronger. At two years into the pandemic, we‚Äôve experienced health gaps and economic losses which have encouraged us to come together for the collective good. The pandemic has also allowed us space and courage to express and live as our truest selves. It‚Äôs taught us to remain resilient and keep our lives, bodies and experiences visibly at the forefront of society. Today, we joyfully celebrate all transgender, non-binary, and gender diverse people!

[Video Description: The TDOV 2022 video is a color video that has a duration of 2 minutes and 24 seconds. The video is shot in a landscape mode in Durham Central Park at the most recent Queer Health & Wellness Fair. In the video, 5 local trans people are interviewed while reciting a prompt and about what Transgender Day of Visibility means to them.]

SQSN is anti anti-violence program of the LGBTQ Center of Durham providing free services for LGBTQIA+ survivors of interpersonal violence in North Carolina. We offer an array of free, non-crisis support services such as support groups, advocacy, and we are currently offering therapy!

Note: we are unable to provide emergency shelter or housing at this time.

You can connect with us via email, our service request form, or anonymously through our free chat service!

Email: advocate@LGBTQCenterofDurham.org
Form: bit.ly/SQSNReq
Anonymous Chat: sqsn.org/chat

üéâ It's that time of year again! We are excited to announce our annual fundraising event, reimagined this year as our Gift of Home Celebration! This year's event will be held on April 10th at 5:30pm, and we are ecstatic to return to hosting at One Eleven Place in Cary!
 
After celebrating the milestone of 5 years in operation last year, we are excited to come together again and celebrate our 6th. 6 years of rehousing neighbors, providing nourishing meals, meeting basic needs, and lighting the way for all who seek vital services in Wake County.
 
Last year was a very special celebration and not just because it was a milestone year. It was our most attended event and, because of you, we raised $85,000, more than double what we raised the prior year. And while we were humbled by this incredible show of support for our communities most vulnerable people, we continue to see increasing levels of homelessness. We need the impact from this year's Gift of Home Celebration to reflect this increase so we can continue to meet the needs of our neighbors. That‚Äôs why we are raising the goal to $150,000.
 
The best way to celebrate our success is by renewing our commitment as a community to support those experiencing homelessness. We invite you to join us for a night of celebrating our efforts, reflecting on the lives we've changed, and looking to the future of our multi-service center so that we can continue to be a beacon of hope for the unhoused in Wake County.
 
To purchase tickets, see sponsorship information, and more, visit the link in our bio!
 
We hope to see you there!

‚öï It wouldn't be a Gift of Home Celebration without WakeMed! 

We almost don't even need to remind you the impact WakeMed has almost daily at Oak City Cares. "Supporters" barely scratch the surface of what they do. They've been with us since day one working hand-in-hand with us to coordinate medical services for our local unhoused neighbors, and to help our hospital system learn how to best serve them. The WakeMed H.E.A.R.T. street outreach team works out of our service center, serving unhoused individuals experiencing chronic illness. They have hosted exercise classes, as well as health empowerment lectures hosted by our very own board member, Dr. Brian Klausner, Medical Director for WakeMed‚Äôs Community Population Health program.

WakeMed and Dr. Klausner are true blessings to our community. In case you haven't heard, Dr. Klausner recently wrote a book titled 'In the Gaps: Better Understanding the Expensive Human Suffering of Chronic Homelessness.' In this book, Dr. K breaks down misconceptions surrounding the the growing crisis of chronic homelessness and how we can all take action to end it through human stories of individuals like those we serve right here at Oak City Cares. 

We hope you'll join Dr. K and all of our friends at WakeMed at this year's Gift of Home Celebration!
